{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608805"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:36:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:36:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16046"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16046"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.23,0,0.03,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8737"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63683"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8737"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49122"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"11188"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20895"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63683"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETeratogens are substances or environmental factors that can cause developmental abnormalities in an embryo or foetus. The effects of teratogens vary depending on the developmental stage at which exposure occurs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following periods of embryonic development is considered most resistant to teratogenic effects?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Weeks 0-2 post-conception","Weeks 3-8 post-conception","Weeks 9-17 post-conception","Weeks 18-26 post-conception","Weeks 27-38 post-conception"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring \u003Cstrong\u003Eweeks 0-2 post-conception\u003C/strong\u003E, embryonic cells are totipotent and can compensate for damage. If severe damage occurs during this period, it typically results in embryonic death rather than congenital abnormalities. This is known as the \u0027all-or-nothing\u0027 period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other periods are more vulnerable to teratogenic effects:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeeks 3-8\u003C/strong\u003E represent the period of organogenesis and are highly susceptible to teratogens\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeeks 9-17\u003C/strong\u003E involve continued organ development and are moderately susceptible\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeeks 18-26\u003C/strong\u003E primarily involve growth and are less susceptible but still vulnerable\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeeks 27-38\u003C/strong\u003E mainly involve maturation but teratogens can still affect growth and brain development\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe resistant period occurs because damaged cells can be replaced by other totipotent cells, or if the damage is too severe, the pregnancy fails before implantation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first two weeks post-conception represent the \u0027resistant period\u0027 where teratogens typically cause either embryonic death or no effect","The \u0027all-or-nothing\u0027 principle applies during the first two weeks of development when embryonic cells are totipotent"],"references":["Alwan S, Chambers CD. Identifying Human Teratogens: An Update. J Pediatr Genet. 2015 Jun;4(2):39-41. doi: 10.1055/s-0035-1556745. PMID: 27617116; PMCID: PMC4918715.","Kaleelullah RA, Garugula N. Teratogenic Genesis in Fetal Malformations. Cureus. 2021 Feb 5;13(2):e13149. doi: 10.7759/cureus.13149. PMID: 33692919; PMCID: PMC7937350.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49122"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16046"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49122"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T11:04:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T11:04:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8737"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63683"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","i